1.1 Basic usage, logical comparisons, and subsetting

TIPS

  • Use Tab to auto complete
  • Use up arrow to get previous command

1.1.1 Create a new project in R Studio

  1. From File menu select New Project…
  2. From New Project Dialog select New Directory
  3. Select New Project as project type.
  4. Give a project name, i.e. “Workshop” and click Create Project button.

1.1.2 Create a new script.

  1. From the File menu select New File > R Script
  2. Save file as “my_Rscript.R”

Write the following commands in code editor of R Studio and run them using icon Run in R Studio

1.1.3 Creating and looking at variables

# create different type of variables, note that the name must not start with a number
# can use <- or = for assignment of values
a <- 100
b <- "hello"
c <- TRUE # can also use T as shortcut
d <- FALSE # can also use F as shortcut

# List variables and content
ls() # list all variables in the memory
## [1] "a" "b" "c" "d"
# To print out content just type the variable name
a
## [1] 100
b
## [1] "hello"
c
## [1] TRUE
d
## [1] FALSE
# You can see the type of variable by using typeof()
typeof(a)
## [1] "double"
typeof(b)
## [1] "character"
typeof(c)
## [1] "logical"
typeof(d)
## [1] "logical"

1.1.4 Logical comparisons

# logical variable
c & d # logical operation: TRUE and FALSE => FALSE
## [1] FALSE
c | d # logical operation: TRUE or FALSE => TRUE
## [1] TRUE
# comparisons
a < 200
## [1] TRUE
a > 50
## [1] TRUE
b == "hello" # equal
## [1] TRUE
b != "hello" # not equal
## [1] FALSE

1.1.6 Factors

# use factor() to create a vector of factors
wk <- factor(c(1:5,2,2,5))
wk
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5 2 2 5
## Levels: 1 2 3 4 5
wk[1] <- "M"  # Why doesn't this work?
wk[1] <- 1 # Fix the value
levels(wk) <- c("M","T","W","Th", "F")
wk
## [1] M  T  W  Th F  T  T  F 
## Levels: M T W Th F
# Can we compare the elements of a factor? NO
wk[1] < wk[3]
## [1] NA
# Create an ordered factor
wk_ordered <- factor(c(1:5,2,2,5),labels=c("M","T","W","Th", "F"), ordered=T)
wk_ordered
## [1] M  T  W  Th F  T  T  F 
## Levels: M < T < W < Th < F
wk_ordered[1]
## [1] M
## Levels: M < T < W < Th < F
# Yes, we can compare now, because it is an ordered factor
wk_ordered[1] < wk_ordered[3]
## [1] TRUE

1.2 Writing functions and using apply

Given a numeric vector, please write a function to get the maximum value of the vector. This is just for our practice, as the max function already exists in R. Use indentation (tab) to make codes more human readable.

get.max <- function(x)
{
    max <- x[1]
    for (i in x)
    {
        if (i > max)
        {
            max <- i
        }
    }
    return(max)
}

a <- c(23.3, 1, 3, 55, 6)
get.max(a)
## [1] 55

1.3 Read and write a file

  1. Read the file https://wd.cri.uic.edu/R/birth_weight.txt into a data frame
  2. Sort the data frame by mother’s age, and write to a new file
  • Data frame columns
    • bwt: baby’s birth weight in ounce (low bwt: < 88 ounces)
    • smoke: 0 - mother is not a smoker, 1 - smoker
    • parity: 0 - child first born, 1 - otherwise
    • gestation: length of pregnancy in days
    • age: mother’s age in years
    • height: mother’s height in inches
    • weight: mother’s pregnancy weight in pounds
bw_data  <- read.delim ("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/R/birth_weight.txt")

head(bw_data)
data_ordered_by_age <- bw_data[order(bw_data$age), ]
head(data_ordered_by_age)
write.table(data_ordered_by_age, file="birth_weight_ordered_by_age.txt", sep="\t",
   quote=F, row.names=F)

1.5 Cleaning and transforming a sample dataset

# Load the tidyverse
library(tidyverse)

# Prepare the dataset
data <- mtcars %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "car")  # move car names to a column

# Example 1: Select only mpg, cyl, and hp
data %>%
  select(car, mpg, cyl, hp)

# Example 2: Rename columns for clarity
data %>%
  rename(miles_per_gallon = mpg,
         horsepower = hp)

# Example 3: Filter cars with mpg greater than 25
data %>%
  filter(mpg > 25)

# Example 4: Filter cars with 4 or 6 cylinders
data %>%
  filter(cyl %in% c(4, 6))

# Example 5: Create a new variable called power_to_weight
data %>%
  mutate(power_to_weight = hp / wt)

# Example 6: Use `case_when` to categorize cars by engine size
data %>%
  mutate(engine_size = case_when(
    disp < 150 ~ "small",
    disp < 300 ~ "medium",
    TRUE ~ "large"
  ))

# Example 7: Average mpg by number of cylinders
data %>%
  group_by(cyl) %>%
  summarise(mean_mpg = mean(mpg))

# Example 8: Count cars per gear group
data %>%
  count(gear)

# Example 9: Pivot mpg, hp, and wt into long format
data_long <- data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(mpg, hp, wt),
               names_to = "variable",
               values_to = "value")

# Example 10: Pivot back to wide format
data_long %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = variable, values_from = value)

# Example 11: Introduce some NA values
data_with_na <- data %>%
  mutate(mpg = replace(mpg, mpg < 20, NA))

# Example 12: Drop rows with NA
data_with_na %>%
  drop_na()

# Example 13: Replace NA with a fixed value
data_with_na %>%
  replace_na(list(mpg = 0))

2.1 Histogram, boxplot, and scatter plot

2.1.1 Histogram

# Example using basic R plotting functions
hist(bw_data$age, main = "Histogram of Mother's Age", xlab = "Mother's Age (years)", col = "red")

# Example using ggplot2
library(ggplot2)

hist_age <- ggplot(data = bw_data, aes(x = age)) +
    geom_histogram(bins = 16, fill = "red", color = "black") +
    theme_classic() +
    labs(title = "Histogram of Mother's Age", x = "Mother's Age (years)")

hist_age

# We can take advantage of the ggplot2 flexibility and display another factor to the histogram
hist_age_parity <- ggplot(data = bw_data, aes(x = age, fill = factor(parity))) +
    geom_histogram(bins = 16, color = "black") +
    theme_classic() +
    labs(
        title = "Proportional Histogram of Mother's Age by Parity",
        x = "Mother's Age (years)",
        y = "Proportion",
        fill = "Parity"
    )

2.7 False discovery rate

2.7.1 Overview

  1. Randomly generate vector wt (size=20) with mean 10 and standard deviation 3.
  2. Randomly generate vector ko (size=20) with mean 10 and standard deviation 3.
  3. Use T-test to test if wt is different from ko, and get p value for the test.
  4. Repeat this procedure 10000 times
  5. Can you find how many \(p < 0.05\)?
  6. Calculate false discovery rate, a.k.a FDR or \(q\) value.

2.7.2 Code

Create an empty vector to store p values

pval <- numeric()

Randomly generate x and y vector with the same means and perform t-test 10000 times

for (i in 1:10000)
{
    wt <- rnorm(20, mean=10, sd=3)
    ko <- rnorm(20, mean=10, sd=3)
    pval[i] <- t.test(wt, ko)$p.value
}

How many tests have \(p < 0.05\)?

length(pval[pval<0.05])
## [1] 475
df <- data.frame(pval = pval)
ggplot(df, aes(x = pval)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, fill = "steelblue", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Histogram of p-values", x = "p-value", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_classic()

summary(pval)
##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max. 
## 0.0003974 0.2479337 0.5028597 0.5023432 0.7533634 0.9999186

Perform FDR correction

FDR <- p.adjust(pval, method="BH")

Now, how many tests have \(q < 0.05\)?

length(FDR[FDR<0.05])
## [1] 0
df <- data.frame(FDR = FDR)
ggplot(df, aes(x = FDR)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = "steelblue", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Histogram of p-values", x = "q-value", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_classic()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

summary(FDR)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9684  0.9881  0.9999  0.9938  0.9999  0.9999
